to the negative 1/5 angstroms.

00:12:02.540 --> 00:12:04.510
And the nucleus of
a hydrogen atom,

00:12:04.510 --> 00:12:07.130
which is really just a proton,
has a radius a little bit--

00:12:07.130 --> 00:12:09.830
and you don't even worry
about this number right here.

00:12:09.830 --> 00:12:12.380
The general idea is, it's
the same order of magnitude.

00:12:12.380 --> 00:12:15.460
It's about 1/10,000th
of an angstrom.

00:12:15.460 --> 00:12:17.740
And just to give a
sense of what it's like,

00:12:17.740 --> 00:12:21.170
if you have the entire, if you
view the entire atomic radius

00:12:21.170 --> 00:12:23.470
to be about an
angstrom, kind of,

00:12:23.470 --> 00:12:26.900
just have a conception
for scale of the atom

00:12:26.900 --> 00:12:29.580
and how much free space
there is in an atom,

00:12:29.580 --> 00:12:33.140
if we even want to think
what is free space.

00:12:33.140 --> 00:12:36.270
Imagine a nucleus
being maybe a marble

00:12:36.270 --> 00:12:38.270
at the center of a
football stadium,

00:12:38.270 --> 00:12:40.200
of a domed football stadium.

00:12:40.200 --> 00:12:44.940
And imagine an electron being a
honey bee just randomly jumping

00:12:44.940 --> 00:12:47.520
around random parts
of that entire volume

00:12:47.520 --> 00:12:49.600
inside of that football stadium.

00:12:49.600 --> 00:12:51.729
And obviously, it's
a quantum honey bee,

00:12:51.729 --> 00:12:53.395
so it can jump around
from spot to spot,

00:12:53.395 --> 00:12:54.860
and it's not easy
to predict where

00:12:54.860 --> 00:12:56.651
it's going to go next,
and all of the rest.

00:12:56.651 --> 00:12:58.940
But that will give you
a sense of the scale

00:12:58.940 --> 00:13:02.730
of the electron and the
proton relative to the atom

00:13:02.730 --> 00:13:03.370
as a whole.

00:13:03.370 --> 00:13:04.870
But even more
crazy, it gives you

00:13:04.870 --> 00:13:14.010
a sense for how empty atoms,
and really all matter really is.

